What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113937 loans with 81 features. Most variables are numeric only few are categorical such as 'BorrowerState' and 'LoanStatus'. We will focus on the 'LoanStatus' its better to understand the unique values that include:

  • 'Completed'
  • 'Current'
  • 'Past Due (1-15 days)'
  • 'Defaulted'
  • 'Chargedoff'
  • 'Past Due (16-30 days)'
  • 'Cancelled'
  • 'Past Due (61-90 days)'
  • 'Past Due (31-60 days)'
  • 'Past Due (91-120 days)'
  • 'FinalPaymentInProgress'
  • 'Past Due (>120 days)'

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting if the loan can be paid in the dataset

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think Employment status together with ownership of property ('IsBorrowerHomeowner') will determine mostly if the loan can be paid or not. But I'm open to explore other features

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 10])
g = sb.PairGrid(data = df, y_vars = numeric_var, x_vars = ['LoanStatus'],
                size = 3, aspect = 2.5)
g.map(boxgrid)
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show();

<Figure size 720x720 with 0 Axes>

When the value of these features increases the number of completed loans and current loans tend to decrease these features are worthwhile exploring before reaching the final conclusion for the financial institution

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Completed loans has high correlation with the employment status, employment status duration and income range. Most number of completed loans were recorded from long employed and with considerable amount of income range. This can be taken to consideration as all of the variables ensure the availability of cashflow which can guarantee the possibility of paying back the loans. There is considerable number of completed and current loans from these groups this can be another proof of confidence in taking the loans.

Other Categorical features include areas where the borrowers come from. With 61,311 US dollars GDP per capita Colorado had highest number of completed loans together with current loans. California and Newyork also have considerable amount of loans that are completed. These are busy stated with much of economic activities which can ensure cashflow to their individuals

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

We expected property ownership to be one of the key features for loans completion as most of financial institutions use houses and other properties as collaterals to offer access to loans. But data shows people with no houses are the one who completed there loans at high number compared to those with property ownership

This suppose to be taken to much of consideration. Financial institutions must modify there rules and procedures to make sure those with considerable cashflow are prioritized

In [56]:
# create faceted heat maps on each variable of loan status under stated monthly income and available bank card credity
g = sb.FacetGrid(data = df, col = 'LoanStatus', col_wrap = 3)

def cuberoot_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """ quick function for computing cube root and cube operations """
    if not inverse:
        return x ** (1/3)
    else:
        return x ** 3

def hist2dgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating heat maps with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    palette = kwargs.pop('color')
    bins_x = np.arange(cuberoot_trans(.2), cuberoot_trans(3.5)+.05, .05)
    bins_y = np.arange(2.4, 4.3+0.1, 0.1)
    plt.hist2d(x, y, bins = [bins_x, bins_y], cmap = palette, cmin = 0.5)
    

def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """ quick function for computing log and power operations """
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)
df['log_BankcardCredit'] = df['AvailableBankcardCredit'].apply(log_trans)
df['log_MonthlyIncome'] = df['StatedMonthlyIncome'].apply(log_trans)

g.map(hist2dgrid, 'log_BankcardCredit', 'log_MonthlyIncome', color = 'inferno_r')
g.set_xlabels('Available Bankcard Credit in USD')
g.set_ylabels('Monthly Income in USD')
plt.show()

For high stated monthly income and available bank card credit there is high number of completed loans together with current loans

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I extended my investigation against stated monthly income and available bank credit balance. There is clear point that completed loans are from high stated monthly income this also goes with the current loans. This also goes to the states of borrowers people from calfornia, Connecticut and Colorado had high chance to pay their loans under both stated monthly income and available bank card credit

There is clear trend also for the income range. USD25,000-49,999 and USD50,000-74,999 has high high number of completed and have loans on the final payment in progress

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Apart from completed loans people with high monthly income also have high number of charged off loans. This can be seen from faceted heat maps

Conclusions¶

Cashflow is essential feature to consider that can guarantee the payment of the loan. Features like stated monthly income, availability bank card credit and income range are the most important to consider. Regardless of places where the borrowers came from as long as there is assured cashflow a loan has high chance to be repaid
